they're extremely different.

00:32:43.620 --> 00:32:46.150
They range from
the very academic

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:49.400
to the extremely personal.

00:32:49.400 --> 00:32:53.380
Some of them are
written, as I mentioned,

00:32:53.380 --> 00:32:54.570
as an exchange of letters.

00:32:54.570 --> 00:32:56.490
There's so many ways
of talking about games,

00:32:56.490 --> 00:33:00.862
and I think there probably will
be a multitude of it happening.

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:07.690
There must be something coming
from the fact that games

00:33:07.690 --> 00:33:09.850
writing and games
journalism largely

00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:14.530
grew-- emerged separate
mainstream media.

00:33:17.074 --> 00:33:18.990
All mainstream media
struggled to cover games.

00:33:18.990 --> 00:33:25.490
I work for a large daily myself,
and it's not entirely clear

00:33:25.490 --> 00:33:28.670
how it should be covered
in circuits like that.

00:33:28.670 --> 00:33:32.747
But I think the way you
can write about the games,

00:33:32.747 --> 00:33:34.830
the language you can use
when talking about games,

00:33:34.830 --> 00:33:37.970
has been affected by the
fact that it has grown

00:33:37.970 --> 00:33:40.430
separate-- online, more
than anything else--

00:33:40.430 --> 00:33:43.470
and separate from the way
we talk about literature,

00:33:43.470 --> 00:33:44.940
for example, or film.

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:46.840
And while it could be
influenced by that,

00:33:46.840 --> 00:33:50.229
it will keep some-- it will
be unique in some way as well.

00:33:50.229 --> 00:33:52.520
DANIEL GOLDBERG: It is actually
a really good question.

00:33:52.520 --> 00:33:55.940
And I think it sort
of connects to some

00:33:55.940 --> 00:33:58.160
of the points we made
earlier about how,

00:33:58.160 --> 00:34:02.080
one, as Linus is saying,
this discourse around games

00:34:02.080 --> 00:34:04.930
has its roots in technology,
which means we've tended

00:34:04.930 --> 00:34:07.024
to evaluate games based
on technological merit,

00:34:07.024 --> 00:34:08.940
because that's the
language that is available.

00:34:08.940 --> 00:34:13.610
And also, it connects to
how the new voices we're

00:34:13.610 --> 00:34:16.130
trying to highlight
in "The State of Play"

00:34:16.130 --> 00:34:19.750
are approaching games from
a different perspective

00:34:19.750 --> 00:34:22.320
and using language that
is, perhaps, closer

00:34:22.320 --> 00:34:26.520
to what traditional cultural
criticism, possibly,

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:27.690
has been about in the past.

00:34:27.690 --> 00:34:30.080
And again, this is something
that is opening doors.

00:34:30.080 --> 00:34:33.130
This means that a new generation
of critics and academics,

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:35.659
but also people who are
interested in games design,

00:34:35.659 --> 00:34:38.540
are able to approach the
field and make something

00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:41.227
interesting out of it without
the necessary background

00:34:41.227 --> 00:34:43.810
or the background in technology
that has really been necessary

00:34:43.810 --> 00:34:44.730
in the past.

00:34:44.730 --> 00:34:47.614
It also comes down to
tools such as Twine.

00:34:47.614 --> 00:34:48.780
Are you familiar with Twine?

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:50.404
Twine, for those of
you who don't know,

00:34:50.404 --> 00:34:53.010
is a platform that
can be used to create

00:34:53.010 --> 00:34:54.760
adventure games or
text-based games

00:34:54.760 --> 00:34:57.534
without a programming
background.

00:34:57.534 --> 00:34:59.400
And [INAUDIBLE] is one
of our contributors

00:34:59.400 --> 00:35:01.930
in the book-- hasn't
got a coding background,

00:35:01.930 --> 00:35:04.746
but creates really fascinating
experiences with a platform

00:35:04.746 --> 00:35:06.120
like Twine, which
doesn't require

00:35:06.120 --> 00:35:07.911
you to have a technical
background in order

00:35:07.911 --> 00:35:09.320
to create games.

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:11.920
That's a really fascinating
thing to talk about, actually.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:14.419
AUDIENCE: For me personally,
one of the things that's always

00:35:14.419 --> 00:35:16.916
been very special about
video games and something

00:35:16.916 --> 00:35:19.040
that's attracted me to it--
and I think that's also

00:35:19.040 --> 00:35:23.190
a very powerful
aspect of games--

00:35:23.190 --> 00:35:26.320
is the fact that when they're
trying to convey a message,

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:28.600
it's always a very
interactive experience.

00:35:28.600 --> 00:35:30.630
So as opposed to reading
something or watching

00:35:30.630 --> 00:35:34.250
something, actually stepping
into the shoes of someone who's

00:35:34.250 --> 00:35:35.900
in this particular
situation does

00:35:35.900 --> 00:35:39.300
a very good job of getting
these kinds of messages across.

00:35:39.300 --> 00:35:45.520
But there has been a very large,
widespread new consumption

00:35:45.520 --> 00:35:48.710
of games through things
like Let's Play on YouTube

00:35:48.710 --> 00:35:50.362
and Twitch TV with streaming.

00:35:50.362 --> 00:35:52.070
And I was wondering
what you guys thought

00:35:52.070 --> 00:35:56.560
about the effects of this
more passive consumption

00:35:56.560 --> 00:35:58.287
of video games as a medium.

00:35:58.287 --> 00:36:00.370
DANIEL GOLDBERG: Another
great question, actually.

00:36:00.370 --> 00:36:00.840
I agree.

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:02.380
And I think a game
like "Cart Life--"

00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:04.796
if you haven't tried "Cart
Life," you should check it out.

00:36:04.796 --> 00:36:07.270
It's a stunning experience
when you're-- as you say,

00:36:07.270 --> 00:36:09.660
games make you identify with
the choices in a way that

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:13.040
isn't really possible in more
passive forms of entertainment.

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:17.250
And by forcing you to identify
with choices like do I

00:36:17.250 --> 00:36:20.812
feed my cat or myself, it's
a heart-wrenching experience.

00:36:20.812 --> 00:36:22.270
It's a very, very
strong experience

00:36:22.270 --> 00:36:25.850
that isn't really possible
outside of games, I think.

00:36:25.850 --> 00:36:28.110
I'm not sure.

00:36:28.110 --> 00:36:31.070
Having said that, some
games are very well--

00:36:31.070 --> 00:36:33.420
narratively-driven games
or story-driven games,

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:36.980
that isn't the whole picture.

00:36:36.980 --> 00:36:41.250
And some games are very
suitable for-- a game

00:36:41.250 --> 00:36:43.500
like "Cart Life" wouldn't
be as strong if you watch it

00:36:43.500 --> 00:36:44.624
as a let's play, of course.

00:36:44.624 --> 00:36:47.580
But watching someone
play-- I'm not sure.

00:36:47.580 --> 00:36:49.310
I'm a big "Dark
Souls" fan myself,

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:51.880
and watching someone play the
"Dark Souls" series on YouTube,

00:36:51.880 --> 00:36:54.480
it's a great
experience, because it's

00:36:54.480 --> 00:36:56.580
sort of-- but it's
also different,

00:36:56.580 --> 00:36:58.890
because it's more
about conveying

00:36:58.890 --> 00:37:01.510
that feeling of playing
something with a friend

00:37:01.510 --> 00:37:04.170
rather than playing it yourself.

00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:08.009
But I think you're right in that
some gameplay experiences can't

00:37:08.009 --> 00:37:10.050
really be conveyed in that
much more passive way,

00:37:10.050 --> 00:37:11.466
or a lot of the
force is, perhaps,

00:37:11.466 --> 00:37:12.810
lost in that transition.

00:37:12.810 --> 00:37:16.932
I haven't got a good answer,
but it's a fascinating point.

00:37:16.932 --> 00:37:19.140
LINUS LARSSON: And every
play through will be unique,

00:37:19.140 --> 00:37:21.910
and every play through
will, to some extent,

00:37:21.910 --> 00:37:23.080
tell a different story.

00:37:23.080 --> 00:37:26.700
So reading about someone
and someone's experience

00:37:26.700 --> 00:37:29.760
with a game, or watching them
play it in a certain way,

00:37:29.760 --> 00:37:34.960
perhaps, this could tell a
different story every time.

00:37:34.960 --> 00:37:38.450
One example-- there's
actually a comedian in Sweden

00:37:38.450 --> 00:37:42.200
who made a point of
trying to play the latest

00:37:42.200 --> 00:37:46.350
Sim City as a Swedish
Social Democrat

00:37:46.350 --> 00:37:48.970
with the tax levels
we have, which isn't

00:37:48.970 --> 00:37:50.080
even possible in the game.

00:37:50.080 --> 00:37:52.410
They're capped way
below what we pay.

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:56.930
But if you max that out to try
to come as close as possible,

00:37:56.930 --> 00:37:59.460
there will be absolute chaos.

00:37:59.460 --> 00:38:02.220
There will be fires everywhere,
and the city you make

00:38:02.220 --> 00:38:05.244
will just break down and
be completely destroyed,

00:38:05.244 --> 00:38:06.160
and everyone will die.

00:38:06.160 --> 00:38:09.400
Well, of course, that's
funny, but it also

00:38:09.400 --> 00:38:13.260
obviously says something
where the makers of that game

00:38:13.260 --> 00:38:14.699
came from.

00:38:14.699 --> 00:38:15.740
DANIEL GOLDBERG: Awesome.

00:38:15.740 --> 00:38:17.430
And again, thanks for
coming down to listen to us.

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:18.346
LINUS LARSSON: Thanks.

00:38:18.346 --> 00:38:21.380
[APPLAUSE]

